"""
MKT Context Commentary — Ezekiel chapters 15–17
Run: python3 scripts/zc-context-ezekiel-15-17-fill.py

Source data used:
- data/interlinear/ezekiel.json
- ANE background: Levantine viticulture, Babylonian vassal-treaty practice,
  birth/abandonment customs in ancient Near East, Hittite/Amorite heritage

Key decisions in this range:
- ch15 vine: woodlessness as proverbial; the fig, olive, and cedar are productive wood;
  the grapevine is not — this is standard ANE horticultural knowledge Ezekiel exploits
- ch16 foundling: birth-abandonment practices (cord, salt, swaddling) are historically attested
  in ancient Near Eastern texts; the Amorite-Hittite parentage evokes the pre-Israelite population
- ch17 two-eagles: the explicit identification as Babylon and Egypt, and Zedekiah's
  broken vassal oath — a covenantal crime in both ANE suzerain-vassal treaty form and before YHWH
"""

import json, pathlib

ROOT = pathlib.Path(__file__).parent.parent

def load_comm(source, book):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    if p.exists():
        return json.loads(p.read_text())
    return {}

def save_comm(source, book, data):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    p.parent.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)
    p.write_text(json.dumps(data, ensure_ascii=False, indent=None))
    print(f'  wrote {p.relative_to(ROOT)}')

def merge_comm(existing, new_data):
    """Merge new_data into existing without overwriting present entries."""
    for ch, verses in new_data.items():
        if ch not in existing:
            existing[ch] = {}
        for v, html in verses.items():
            if v not in existing[ch]:
                existing[ch][v] = html

EZEKIEL_CONTEXT = {
"15": {
    "1": '<p>Short wisdom-allegory. The vine was Israel\'s most recognized national symbol: Psalm 80:8-16 pictures Israel as a vine transplanted from Egypt; Isaiah 5:1-7 is the famous Song of the Vineyard; Hosea 10:1 calls Israel "a luxuriant vine." The gold vine was displayed prominently on Herod\'s Temple. Ezekiel exploits the symbol by arguing from its most uncomfortable implication: the grapevine produces wood that is practically useless for construction or toolmaking.</p>',
    "2": '<p>Ancient Levantine carpenters and craftsmen relied on cedar (from Lebanon), oak, and olive wood. Grapevine stems — twisted, knotted, with pithy interior — cannot be made into planks, posts, or pegs. The rhetorical question "Is wood taken from it to make something useful?" expects "no" from any audience familiar with viticulture. A vine\'s only value is its fruit and, when the vine exhausts itself or is diseased, as fuel. The allegory strips Israel\'s prestigious self-image as YHWH\'s vine to its most basic physical reality.</p>',
    "3": '<p><strong>Woodworking in ancient Canaan</strong>: Pegs (<em>yated</em>) were critical structural and household items — used for tents, walls, and hanging implements. The specific question "can a peg be made from it to hang any vessel?" uses a completely practical test. Grapevine wood was too irregular, soft, and short-sectioned for such use. Even before the burning of v.4-5, the vine fails the functional test: its identity as fruit-bearer means it has no secondary structural utility.</p>',
    "4": '<p>The burning scenario introduces a new level of uselessness: burned vine wood (charred ends, fire-damaged middle) is even less serviceable than unburned vine wood. ANE domestic fires used vine branches and pruned wood as fuel; this was their natural end. Once consumed or charred, the vine wood is worthless even for fuel. The double worthlessness — useless before burning, more useless after — structures the allegory\'s argument: Israel has been partially "burned" by YHWH\'s first judgments (partial captivity) and is still being worthless.</p>',
    "5": '<p>The burned-vine metaphor applies directly to Jerusalem\'s residents who have survived preliminary judgments. The "burned" portions of Israel are those already in exile (Jehoiachin\'s deportation, 597 BCE). The remaining inhabitants have witnessed the first burning and are now more useless than before — not repentant, not reformed, but like charred wood that has neither the original beauty of unburned timber nor any structural strength. The allegory is structurally pessimistic: there is no useful end for vine-wood regardless of the stage of its burning.</p>',
    "6": '<p>YHWH draws the explicit application: as vine wood is given to fire as fuel, so the inhabitants of Jerusalem. The firewood use of grapevine was universal in ancient Palestine — every family burned vine prunings. The image is demythologizing: the glorious city of David\'s dynasty is, from a wood-utility perspective, no different from the vine trimmings burned in every village courtyard. The national pride attached to Jerusalem is punctured by a horticultural fact.</p>',
    "7": '<p><strong>Fire as divine judgment</strong>: The repeated fire-from-fire construction ("though they escape from fire, fire shall consume them") reflects the ANE siege-warfare context. Survivors of one Babylonian campaign found themselves facing another. The 597 BCE deportation left survivors; the 586 BCE destruction left more survivors in the land; even those survivors would face the 582 BCE further deportation (Jer 52:30). Each "escape" only delayed, not prevented, the consuming fire. The <em>yeda\'tem</em> formula closes the allegory.</p>',
    "8": '<p>The allegory closes with the land made desolate because of unfaithfulness — <em>ma\'al</em> (breach of covenant, trespass against sacred things). The term <em>ma\'al</em> is a covenant-crime term: it describes the violation of the trust relationship between Israel and YHWH, specifically the appropriation for common use of what belongs to YHWH. The land\'s desolation is the covenant-curse consequence (Lev 26:32-35) of Israel\'s consistent failure to produce the fruit for which YHWH planted the vine.</p>'
},
"16": {
    "1": '<p>The longest chapter in Ezekiel and one of the most graphic in the entire Hebrew Bible. The allegory deploys the marriage metaphor that runs through Hosea (1-3), Jeremiah (2-3), and Isaiah (50; 54; 62). What makes Ezekiel\'s version distinct is its explicit grounding of Jerusalem\'s identity in its pre-Israelite inhabitants — a theological provocation to audiences who traced Jerusalem\'s sanctity to David\'s conquest.</p>',
    "2": '<p><strong>"Make known to Jerusalem her abominations"</strong>: The judicial proceeding is explicit — this is a court presentation of evidence. The allegory is forensic in structure: charges → evidence → verdict → sentence → conditional restoration. The audience (exiles who idealized Jerusalem) must hear the full weight of what Jerusalem had become before they can receive the restoration promises of ch 37-48.</p>',
    "3": '<p><strong>Amorite father, Hittite mother</strong>: Jerusalem\'s Canaanite heritage before David\'s conquest (2 Sam 5:6-9). The Jebusites who held Jerusalem were part of the pre-Israelite Canaanite population; Ezekiel traces their ethnic genealogy to Amorites (inhabitants of the highlands and Transjordan) and Hittites (likely the Neo-Hittite populations of Syria-Canaan, distinct from the Anatolian Hittite empire). The genealogy is a deliberate desacralization: Jerusalem has no inherent holiness from its origins — only from YHWH\'s election of it.</p>',
    "4": '<p><strong>Birth abandonment practices in the ancient Near East</strong>: Ezekiel describes the standard birth-care that Jerusalem (the foundling) did NOT receive. Cutting the umbilical cord, washing with water, rubbing with salt (a practice attested in ancient Near Eastern medical texts and still practiced in some traditional cultures), and wrapping in swaddling cloths (<em>hutchal chatatuleich</em>) were the normative sequence for a newborn. Salt rubbing was believed to firm and cleanse the skin. The catalog of un-received care is detailed and specific — the allegory is medically informed.</p>',
    "5": '<p><strong>Exposure of infants in the ancient Near East</strong>: Infant exposure — abandoning a newborn in an open field — was practiced across the ancient Mediterranean and Near East when families could not or chose not to raise a child. The Mesopotamian birth-legend of Sargon of Akkad involves abandonment and rescue. Greek exposure (ekthesis) was legally regulated. In the Hebrew Bible, Moses\' abandonment and rescue is the closest parallel. <em>Vatashlichi el-pnei hasadeh</em> (\'and you were thrown out into the open field\') — Jerusalem\'s first condition was total vulnerability, not inherent nobility.</p>',
    "6": '<p><strong>"I passed by and saw you kicking in your blood"</strong>: The twice-repeated command <em>Bachayayich chyi</em> (\'in your blood, live!\') is the divine life-word spoken to the abandoned infant. The image is of an infant still thrashing in birth-blood, umbilical cord uncleaned, covered in fluid — the most vulnerable possible state. YHWH\'s election of Jerusalem is thus presented as pure grace with zero merit basis: the chosen one is at the absolute nadir of existence. The ANE context makes the double "live!" resonant — it is a counter-command to the implicit death-by-abandonment the city was left for.</p>',
    "7": '<p><strong>The growth of the foundling</strong>: Jerusalem is described growing up "like a plant of the field" — an uncultivated, unattended but organic development. The physical maturity described — breasts formed, hair grown — uses standard ANE descriptions of adolescent female development. The child grew but remained "naked and bare" (<em>eroma ve\'erya</em>) — without the social covering that comes from belonging to a household and community. The vulnerability of uncovered status in ancient Near Eastern society (where clothing marked social identity and protection) underlies the nakedness motif.</p>',
    "8": '<p><strong>The spreading of the garment corner</strong>: <em>Ufros kenafi alayich</em> (\'I spread the corner of my garment over you\'): a formal adoption/marriage gesture well attested in the ancient Near East. Ruth 3:9 uses identical language when Ruth asks Boaz to \'spread your wing over your servant\' — a proposal of marriage/protection. Ezekiel 16:8 uses the same gesture as YHWH\'s formal act of covenantal betrothal. The phrase <em>ba\'et dodim</em> (\'at the time of love/betrothal\') marks the marriage moment; the covenant (<em>brit</em>) formalizes it.</p>',
    "9": '<p><strong>Washing, anointing, and dressing as wedding preparation</strong>: The sequence in vv. 9-14 parallels ancient Near Eastern wedding preparation rituals documented in Mesopotamian and Ugaritic texts. The bride was washed (<em>erchatzech</em>), anointed with oil (<em>va\'asuchech beshamen</em>), clothed (<em>va\'albisech riqdamah</em>), and adorned with jewelry. Blood here refers to the birth-blood of v.6 — the allegory returns to that beginning moment and now offers the purification that was initially denied. YHWH as husband completes the care that Jerusalem\'s original parents failed to provide.</p>',
    "10": '<p><strong>The bridal garments</strong>: The specific fabrics in vv. 10-13 are luxury items in the ancient Near Eastern world. <em>Riqdamah</em> (embroidered/multi-colored fabric) — the same as Joseph\'s "coat of many colors" (Gen 37:3); a costly garment requiring skilled needlework. <em>Tachasim</em> (fine leather/porpoise/dugong skin) — the same material used for the tabernacle coverings (Ex 25:5), indicating extraordinary quality. <em>Shesh</em> (fine linen — Egyptian byssus) — the luxury fabric of Egypt, used for priestly garments and royal dress.</p>',
    "11": '<p><strong>Jewelry in the ancient Near East</strong>: Nose-ring, bracelets, necklace — the standard categories of feminine jewelry in Iron Age Canaan and Mesopotamia. Archaeological finds from Iron Age Levantine sites (including Jerusalem) consistently include these items in wealthy tombs and deposits. The jewelry represents YHWH\'s gift of beauty and status to the city he made his own — Jerusalem\'s historical prosperity under David and Solomon expressed allegorically as bridal adornment.</p>',
    "12": '<p><strong>The golden crown</strong>: <em>Va\'eten etz-niferet tif\'eret al-roshech</em> (\'and I put a glorious crown on your head\'): possibly referring to Solomon\'s construction of the temple and the golden decorations. The crown on the head is the final element of the queenly transformation — from naked abandoned infant to crowned queen. The sequence of gifts culminates in royal headgear, making the foundling not merely a bride but a queen. Jerusalem\'s theological status as YHWH\'s dwelling-place is expressed through the queenly-adornment allegory.</p>',
    "13": '<p><strong>"You became exceedingly beautiful and advanced to royalty"</strong>: The summary statement of the city\'s rise. <em>Va\'itsla\'achi limluchah</em> (\'you advanced to royalty/kingship\'): the verb <em>tsalach</em> (to prosper, advance) combined with <em>mluchah</em> (kingship) — Jerusalem became the royal city, the seat of the Davidic dynasty. The historical memory being allegorized: David\'s capture of Jerusalem (2 Sam 5), Solomon\'s temple-building, and the city\'s status as the political-religious capital of the united kingdom.</p>',
    "14": '<p><strong>Fame among the nations</strong>: <em>Va\'yetze lach shem bagoyim beyofyech</em> (\'your fame went out among the nations because of your beauty\'): the Solomonic era is evoked — the Queen of Sheba\'s visit (1 Kgs 10:1-13), the fame of Solomon\'s wisdom and wealth reaching the surrounding nations. <em>Ki kalil hu betifarter asher samtiy alayich</em> (\'for it was perfect through the splendor I placed on you\'): YHWH takes full credit for the beauty. Jerusalem\'s fame was not self-made but divine gift.</p>',
    "15": '<p><strong>"But you trusted in your beauty"</strong>: The pivot. The idiomatic <em>vativtechi veyofyech</em> (\'you trusted in your beauty\') uses <em>batach</em> (trust/rely) — the same word used for trusting in YHWH (Ps 4:5; 9:10). Jerusalem transferred its ultimate reliance from the giver of beauty to beauty itself. The prostitution (<em>tizneh</em>) to every passer-by echoes the ANE practice of cult prostitution but also political-military alliances — seeking security through alliance with foreign powers rather than trust in YHWH.</p>',
    "16": '<p><strong>Cultic objects from garments</strong>: Using YHWH\'s gifted garments to make high-place decorations. The practice of adorning bamot (high-place altars) with textiles and colorful coverings is well attested in ANE religion — Canaanite cult sites featured decorated sacred poles (asherim) and draped altars. Using YHWH\'s bridal gifts for pagan cult purposes is the allegory\'s most pointed statement of the inversion: the tokens of the marriage covenant become the props of the adulterous worship.</p>',
    "17": '<p><strong>Images made from YHWH\'s gold and silver</strong>: The idols (<em>tzalmei zachar</em>, male-figure images) made from YHWH\'s jewelry. The making of anthropomorphic male cult statues was common across the ancient Near East — Canaanite Baal figurines, Egyptian divine statues, Mesopotamian temple cult-images. The Deuteronomy 7:25 prohibition on keeping the gold and silver of Canaanite idols is the reverse situation here: Israel is now making idols from YHWH\'s own precious metals.</p>',
    "18": '<p><strong>Clothing idols with embroidered garments</strong>: The practice of dressing divine statues was central to Mesopotamian religion — elaborate garments were made for the statues of Marduk, Ishtar, and other deities; clothing and feeding the divine statue (washing its face, dressing it, setting food before it) was the core of official temple cult in Babylonia (the <em>mis pi</em> and <em>pit pi</em> rituals). Ezekiel\'s audience in Babylon would have witnessed this practice directly. Jerusalem\'s apostasy here adopts Mesopotamian cult practice.</p>',
    "19": '<p><strong>Food offerings to idols</strong>: YHWH\'s food gifts (fine flour, oil, honey) set before idols as offerings. The Ugaritic texts document food offerings to Baal and El; Mesopotamian texts describe elaborate meals set before divine statues. The irony is bitter: the agricultural abundance YHWH gave Israel (Deut 8:7-10) is used to feed the idols who had nothing to do with its production. <em>Vayehi ne\'um Adonai YHWH</em>: the divine testimony formula — YHWH witnesses the misappropriation.</p>',
    "20": '<p><strong>Child sacrifice</strong>: The accusation of sacrificing sons and daughters to idols marks the most severe level of apostasy. The Molech cult (Lev 18:21; 2 Kgs 23:10; Jer 32:35) involved child sacrifice at the Topheth in the Ben Hinnom valley south of Jerusalem (later Gehenna). 2 Kings 16:3 and 21:6 explicitly accuse Ahaz and Manasseh of passing children through fire. Ezekiel\'s allegory reaches this climax as the most terrible form of the prostitution — the children born of the marriage are killed to feed the lovers.</p>',
    "21": '<p><strong>"You slaughtered my sons"</strong>: The possessive <em>banai</em> (my sons) — YHWH claims the children as his own, born from the covenant marriage. The making-pass-through-fire (<em>lehavaer lahem</em>) as a sacrificial act for the idols is described with the verb for making whole-burnt offerings. The Topheth site and Molech worship were specifically associated with the kings of Judah (Manasseh: 2 Kgs 21:6; Ahaz: 2 Kgs 16:3) — the same dynasty YHWH had established as his royal representative.</p>',
    "22": '<p>The tragic irony: all the abominations were done without remembering the days of abandonment and YHWH\'s rescue. The foundling who was given everything has completely forgotten the original destitution. The memory of grace (<em>lo zakart et-yemei ne\'uraiich</em>, \'you did not remember the days of your youth\') is the failure that makes the apostasy most egregious — not merely ingratitude in the abstract but the specific failure to remember the dramatic rescue that defined the relationship.</p>',
    "23": '<p>The "woe to you" (<em>vay vay lach</em>) is a funerary lament formula — the same root as the word for "woe" in prophetic judgment speeches. It introduces the full catalogue of the prostitution\'s political dimension. After the cultic apostasy (idols, child sacrifice), Ezekiel now addresses the political prostitution — seeking security through alliances with surrounding empires rather than relying on YHWH.</p>',
    "24": '<p><strong>High places and raised shrines</strong>: <em>Gev</em> (a mound, elevated platform) and <em>ramah</em> (high place, raised shrine) — the technical terms for outdoor cult installations. The construction of these at every open space in Jerusalem is hyperbolically described (<em>vatabniy-lach gev bechol-rechov</em>) to convey the totality of the apostasy. Archaeological evidence from Iron Age II Jerusalem confirms multiple cultic installations beyond the temple, including the Silwan village tomb shrines and various bamot installations.</p>',
    "25": '<p>The phrase <em>el-kol-over</em> (\'to every passer-by\') intensifies the prostitution allegory — no boundary or selectivity, complete indiscrimination. The \'spreading of the legs\' (<em>vatifshi et-raglayich</em>) is graphic sexual language that would have shocked Ezekiel\'s hearers. The specific charge that Jerusalem multiplied its prostitution to provoke YHWH connects the political-religious alliances to covenantal infidelity — each treaty with a foreign power was a theological act of spouse-betrayal.</p>',
    "26": '<p><strong>Egypt as sexual partner</strong>: <em>Gedolei basar</em> (\'large of flesh/genitals\'): a sexually explicit description of Egypt — the large-membered neighbor — as the first partner in the political prostitution. The 8th-century Assyrian crisis had pushed Judah toward Egypt as a counterbalance; Hezekiah\'s appeal to Egypt (Isa 30:1-5; 31:1-3) is the historical background. Isaiah explicitly condemned the Egyptian alliance as worthless. Ezekiel uses sexually graphic language to convey the theological obscenity of dependence on Egypt over YHWH.</p>',
    "27": '<p><strong>The Philistines</strong>: YHWH\'s first judgment — reducing Jerusalem\'s allotment and handing her to the will of hostile Philistine daughters (<em>pelishtiyot habo\'shot midark\'ech zimah</em>, \'Philistines who were ashamed of your lewd conduct\'). The irony: even the Philistines — Israel\'s traditional enemies, themselves pagan — were embarrassed by Jerusalem\'s behavior. The Philistine daughters serve as a rhetorical foil: pagan nations recognize Jerusalem\'s conduct as outrageous while Jerusalem is oblivious to the shame.</p>',
    "28": '<p><strong>Assyria</strong>: The Assyrian alliance follows Egypt in the political prostitution catalogue. The historical referent is Ahaz\'s appeal to Tiglath-Pileser III of Assyria (2 Kgs 16:7-9; Isa 7-8), offering tribute and allegiance in exchange for military help against the Aram-Ephraim coalition. Isaiah 7:14-17 is addressed to Ahaz in that context. The successive alliances — Egypt, Assyria, Babylon (vv. 28-29) — trace Judah\'s diplomatic history through the 8th and 7th centuries.</p>',
    "29": '<p><strong>Chaldea (Babylon)</strong>: The Chaldean alliance — the final political prostitution in the sequence. <em>Ve\'lo sava\'at</em> (\'and you were still not satisfied\'): the serial nature of the political prostitution — each alliance only stimulated appetite for more. Historically, Manasseh\'s submission to Babylon (2 Chr 33:11), Jehoiakim\'s rebellion and resubmission, and Zedekiah\'s vacillation between Babylonian submission and Egyptian alliance represent the Chaldean phase.</p>',
    "30": '<p><strong>"How weak your heart is"</strong>: <em>Ma amulah libatech</em> — alternatively translated \'how raging is your heart\' (reading <em>amulah</em> from <em>amal</em>, to be sick/weak, or from <em>amol</em>, to pine/languish). The description of Jerusalem as worse than a professional prostitute (<em>zona</em>) because she gives gifts rather than receiving them inverts the economics of prostitution. Ancient prostitutes received payment; Jerusalem paid her partners. The irrationality of the arrangement (paying for the privilege of betraying YHWH) is the point: it is not economic calculation but compulsive spiritual infidelity.</p>',
    "31": '<p><strong>The anti-prostitute</strong>: The allegory\'s most cutting comparison — Jerusalem reversed the typical prostitution economics. ANE prostitution (both secular and cultic/qedeshah) involved payment to the prostitute. Jerusalem\'s alliances involved paying tribute (<em>natan etnan</em>, giving payment) to the partners rather than receiving it. This inverted economics makes Jerusalem worse than a professional prostitute from a pure economic rationality standpoint — she gives, does not receive.</p>',
    "32": '<p><strong>The unfaithful wife</strong>: The marriage metaphor dominates: <em>ha\'isha hamena\'efet</em> (\'the wife who commits adultery\') — the legal category is adultery, not merely prostitution. The distinction is significant: a prostitute is not married and thus not breaking a covenant; an adulterous wife betrays a specific covenant relationship. YHWH and Jerusalem are in a covenant marriage; Jerusalem\'s behavior is not merely morally bad but legally criminal within the covenant framework.</p>',
    "33": '<p><strong>Payment direction</strong>: All prostitutes receive payment; Jerusalem alone pays her clients. The rhetorical point: Jerusalem\'s alliances were purchased — tribute paid to Assyria, Egypt, and Babylon. Each alliance cost real wealth that YHWH had given Jerusalem. The financial flow makes Jerusalem\'s unfaithfulness economically irrational as well as covenantally criminal — she spent her dowry gifts (the wealth YHWH gave) on the very act of betraying the giver.</p>',
    "34": '<p>The uniqueness of Jerusalem\'s prostitution — inverted from all normal patterns. The reversal is three-fold: no one seeks Jerusalem for the act (Jerusalem initiates); Jerusalem pays rather than receives; Jerusalem gives gifts rather than taking them. This triple inversion is the basis for the verdict: Jerusalem is worse than any comparable case because her behavior has no parallel, not even in the worst forms of human infidelity.</p>',
    "35": '<p>Direct address: <em>zona</em> (prostitute) — the judicial title applied to Jerusalem in the accusation. The formal address opens the sentencing section. The prophetic indictment in ancient Israelite legal procedure moved from charges (vv. 1-34) to formal accusation (v.35) to verdict/sentence (vv. 36-43). The structural shift here marks the transition to judgment.</p>',
    "36": '<p><strong>"Because your bronze was poured out"</strong>: <em>Ya\'an hishafech nechushtech</em> — disputed: either \'your bronze/lust\' (reading <em>nechoshet</em>) or \'your flow\' (sexual fluid). The context of verse 36 confirms that the sexual license with partners, along with child sacrifice and idols, is the indictment basis. The three-fold accusation — idolatry, political prostitution, and child sacrifice — is the grounds for the three-fold judgment that follows.</p>',
    "37": '<p><strong>The gathering of lovers for exposure</strong>: The legal punishment for adultery in ancient Near East typically involved public exposure and shaming. Mesopotamian law codes (Code of Hammurabi §129; Middle Assyrian Laws §§13-16) prescribed death or bodily mutilation for adultery. YHWH\'s sentence gathers all the lovers (the nations with whom Jerusalem made alliances) to witness and participate in the punishment — the punishing agency being the very parties who were the instruments of the apostasy.</p>',
    "38": '<p><strong>"I will judge you as women who commit adultery and shed blood are judged"</strong>: The legal standard — combining adultery and bloodshed (child sacrifice). Both were capital offenses in Israelite law (Lev 20:10 for adultery; Lev 20:2 for Molech-worship involving child sacrifice). The allegory moves from metaphor to explicit legal language: the sentence is the death penalty of an adulterous murderess. The juridical character of the chapter is unambiguous — this is a trial with YHWH as both accuser and judge.</p>',
    "39": '<p><strong>Stripping and public exposure</strong>: The punishment fits the crime in an inverse way — the beautiful garments, jewelry, and adornments that YHWH gave (vv. 10-13) are stripped away by the enraged lovers (the nations). The stripping and nakedness is both literal (conquest and plunder) and symbolic (the removal of the status and beauty YHWH gave). The same nations that profited from the political alliances become the instruments of judgment — Babylon itself strips what Jerusalem prostituted herself to gain.</p>',
    "40": '<p><strong>Stoning and sword</strong>: Both Deuteronomy 22:21-24 (stoning for adultery) and Ezekiel\'s fuller legal picture apply here. The <em>qahal</em> (assembly/mob) executes the sentence — the corporate community as the instrument of legal judgment. The sword adds the military dimension: the Babylonian army is the assembly that stones Jerusalem. The double execution method (stoning + sword) represents both the civil-legal and military-political dimensions of the coming judgment.</p>',
    "41": '<p><strong>Burning of houses</strong>: The final judgment element — fire consuming the houses (<em>bateicha bisrefot eish</em>). The Babylonian destruction of Jerusalem in 586 BCE involved burning the palace, the temple, and the houses of the leading citizens (2 Kgs 25:9; Jer 52:13). The burning closes the allegory\'s judgment sequence: stripped, stoned, cut with swords, houses burned. The cessation of "prostitution" (<em>veshavatti zinutech min-ha\'aretz</em>) is the purpose of the judgment — not merely punishment but the termination of the behavior.</p>',
    "42": '<p><strong>"I will satisfy my fury against you"</strong>: <em>Vahinachothi chamati bakh</em> (\'and my fury will be satisfied/rested in you\'): the same <em>nuach-chamath</em> (fury resting/satisfied) from 5:13; 21:17. The divine fury is not arbitrary but proportionate and finite — it reaches completion when the judgment is carried out. The jealousy (<em>qin\'ah</em>) that drove the judgment also reaches its end: <em>lo-eqna od</em> (\'I will be jealous no more\'). The divine passion (both the love and the anger) comes to completion through the enacted judgment.</p>',
    "43": '<p>The purpose of the judgment is not eternal punishment but remediation: after the fury is spent, Jerusalem will remember and be ashamed — the shame will prevent repetition. The logic is therapeutic as well as punitive: the experience of judgment breaks the cycle. The same logic appears in Hosea 2:14-15 — the wilderness experience, painful as it is, is meant to restore the original covenant relationship.</p>',
    "44": '<p><strong>The proverb "like mother, like daughter"</strong>: <em>Ken-imah kitah</em> — the social proverb about inherited behavior patterns. In the ancient world, character was understood as fundamentally heritable through family and ethnicity. The proverb works against Jerusalem by identifying her mother as the Hittite/Amorite Canaanite population — she has inherited the religious and moral character of the original inhabitants whom Israel was supposed to displace and replace, not emulate.</p>',
    "45": '<p><strong>Three sisters oracle: Jerusalem and her sisters</strong>: The comparison of Jerusalem to Samaria and Sodom establishes a theological hierarchy of guilt. Samaria (the northern kingdom) and Sodom (the proverbial worst city of the pre-Israelite period, Gen 18-19) are both bad — but Jerusalem is worse than both. The rhetorical device is designed to puncture Jerusalem\'s sense of superiority: the city of David\'s temple is not better than but worse than the two most notorious negative exemplars in Israel\'s religious tradition.</p>',
    "46": '<p><strong>Samaria (elder sister) and Sodom (younger)</strong>: The geographic designation — <em>Shomron ibatach al-smolech</em> (Samaria on the left = north) and <em>veachot veqetanah mimmenach hayoshevet al-yeminech</em> (your smaller sister on the right = south) — Sodom. The relative sizes establish the hierarchy: Samaria is the larger/older sister, Sodom the smaller/younger. Jerusalem in the middle represents the worst of both worlds and simultaneously worse than either.</p>',
    "47": '<p><strong>Sodom\'s sin according to Ezekiel</strong>: In vv. 49-50, Ezekiel provides the most explicit OT statement of Sodom\'s sin: pride (<em>gaon</em>), abundance of food (<em>sova lechem</em>), and comfortable rest (<em>shalvat hashalevot</em>) leading to failure to help the poor (<em>lo-chazzekah yad ani ve\'evyon</em>). This is a significant departure from the Genesis 19 reading that focuses on the attempted gang rape — Ezekiel\'s Sodom is guilty of economic pride and indifference to the poor, not primarily sexual violence. The allegorical use of Sodom here reflects a tradition of interpreting Sodom\'s sin in social-justice terms (cf. Isa 1:10-17).</p>',
    "48": '<p>The comparative structure continues: Sodom did not do what Jerusalem has done (<em>lo asta kachet banoteha</em>). The superlative guilt of Jerusalem is established not by minimizing Sodom\'s sin but by asserting that Jerusalem\'s sins exceeded even Sodom\'s. The logic is theological: Jerusalem had access to YHWH\'s covenant, his Torah, his prophets, his temple — and still exceeded Sodom. Greater light, greater responsibility, greater guilt.</p>',
    "49": '<p><strong>Sodom\'s specific guilt</strong>: Pride, food abundance, and ease (<em>shalvah</em> — security, ease, prosperity). The <em>shalvah</em> vocabulary connects to the danger of affluence identified in Deuteronomy 8:10-14 — when Israel ate and was satisfied, they risked forgetting YHWH. Sodom\'s sin of omission — not strengthening the poor — reflects the covenant obligation of solidarity with the vulnerable that runs from Exodus 22:21-27 through Amos and Isaiah. Ezekiel\'s Sodom is a cautionary tale about prosperity theology gone wrong.</p>',
    "50": '<p><strong>Sodom\'s haughty behavior</strong>: <em>Vatirganah vatyash\'nah toevah lefanai</em> (\'they became arrogant and committed abomination before me\'): the <em>toevah</em> (abomination) here may include the sexual violence of Genesis 19 but is preceded by the pride and neglect described in v.49. The social-justice reading does not exclude the sexual component but contextualizes it within a broader portrait of moral collapse driven by economic privilege. YHWH\'s removal of Sodom is the response to the full syndrome, not a single act.</p>',
    "51": '<p><strong>Samaria less guilty than Jerusalem</strong>: Samaria\'s sins are taken as given — the northern kingdom\'s idolatry and eventual destruction (722 BCE by Assyria) were the cautionary tale cited throughout Deuteronomy\'s perspective on the monarchy. But Jerusalem actually made Samaria appear righteous by comparison (<em>vatatsddiq et-achotaiyich</em>). The superlative guilt-by-comparison is a rhetorical climax: Judah looked down on Israel\'s apostasy while exceeding it.</p>',
    "52": '<p><strong>Jerusalem as advocate for her sisters by her own sin</strong>: The irony of justification-by-comparison — Jerusalem\'s sins make Samaria and Sodom look righteous. <em>Vatissi cherpat</em> (\'you bear your shame\'): the communal shame is Jerusalem\'s to carry alone because the comparison shows she is uniquely guilty. The role reversal — the religious capital becoming the most guilty — is the allegory\'s culminating shock.</p>',
    "53": '<p><strong>The restoration of Sodom and Samaria</strong>: The surprising turn — YHWH will restore the fortunes of Sodom (<em>veshavti et-shevitat sedom uvnoteha</em>) and Samaria alongside Jerusalem. The restoration of these two notorious sinners makes Jerusalem\'s restoration entirely a matter of grace, not merit. If even Sodom is to be restored, then Jerusalem\'s restoration cannot be based on Jerusalem\'s relative righteousness.</p>',
    "54": '<p>The humiliation implicit in the restoration promise: Jerusalem must be restored alongside Sodom, not instead of or above Sodom. The pride that was a central element of Jerusalem\'s sin (pride in the David/Zion traditions) is addressed by placing Jerusalem in precisely the company she would have found most humiliating. The restoration is real but comes with a permanent debasement of the status-pride that led to the apostasy.</p>',
    "55": '<p><strong>The return to "former estate"</strong>: <em>Ve\'achotayich sedom uvnoteha tashovenah liqdmatahn</em> (\'and your sisters — Sodom and her daughters — shall return to their former estate\'): the word <em>qadmat</em> (former state/beginning) suggests a return to pre-judgment condition. The restoration is not a new creation but a recovery — both for Sodom and Jerusalem, the former conditions will be re-established. For Jerusalem this means the covenant relationship; for Sodom this apparently means existence as populated communities (the eschatological vision is deliberately expansive).</p>',
    "56": '<p>Sodom was not even mentioned in Jerusalem\'s "mouth" in the day of her pride (<em>begaon ga\'oniich</em>). The proud days of Solomon and the Davidic peak were the times when Jerusalem would not lower herself to mention Sodom — so distant did Jerusalem consider herself from that paradigmatic sinner. Now the allegorical reversal shows Jerusalem sharing Sodom\'s fate and Sodom sharing Jerusalem\'s future restoration.</p>',
    "57": '<p><strong>"Before your wickedness was uncovered"</strong>: The exposure of Jerusalem\'s sin by the Babylonian conquest. The daughters of Aram (Syria) and Philistia who scorned Jerusalem — the surrounding nations whose contempt would have stung Jerusalem\'s pride. The dating is suggestive: before the fall, Jerusalem seemed superior; after the fall, her sin is visible to all. The nations who were scorned by Jerusalem in her prosperity now scorn her in her ruin.</p>',
    "58": '<p>The statement of deserved judgment: <em>et-zimmathech ve\'et-to\'avotayich at nesatim</em> (\'your lewdness and your abominations you shall bear\'). The covenant principle of bearing one\'s own iniquity (individual accountability) is applied to the city as a whole — Jerusalem carries the weight of its accumulated sin. The justice of the judgment is reaffirmed: this is not arbitrary destruction but the earned consequence of the documented apostasy.</p>',
    "59": '<p><strong>The broken covenant</strong>: <em>Ki koh amar Adonai YHWH ve\'asiti otach ka\'asher asit asher-vazit alah lehafar brit</em> (\'for thus says the Lord YHWH: I will deal with you as you have dealt — you who despised the oath by breaking the covenant\'). The covenant-breaking is now stated in its clearest legal form. The <em>alah</em> (oath/curse) and <em>brit</em> (covenant) are the two components of the Sinai covenant: the oath that sealed it and the covenant relationship it established. Jerusalem broke both.</p>',
    "60": '<p><strong>The everlasting covenant</strong>: After all the judgment, the pivot: <em>Vezakharti ani et-briti otach bimei ne\'uraiich</em> (\'but I myself will remember my covenant with you in the days of your youth\'). The return to the foundling moment — YHWH remembers the original covenant of vv. 8-14. Despite Jerusalem\'s comprehensive unfaithfulness, YHWH remembers. The asymmetry is total: Jerusalem forgot (v.22); YHWH remembers. The result: <em>brit olam</em> (everlasting covenant) — the eschatological covenant that transcends the broken Sinai covenant and is grounded purely in divine fidelity.</p>',
    "61": '<p><strong>Shame and the receiving of the sisters</strong>: Jerusalem will remember her ways (<em>tizkerevat derachayich</em>) and be ashamed when she receives Samaria and Sodom as daughters — a role reversal from the elder-sister pride of v.56. The \'receiving as daughters\' (adopting the previously scorned) is the concrete form of the humiliation that accompanies restoration. The restoration is real but not comfortable: it comes with the collapse of the status hierarchy that fed Jerusalem\'s pride.</p>',
    "62": '<p><strong>"I will establish my covenant with you"</strong>: The covenant formula completed at the restoration: <em>vahaqqimoti ani et-briti itach</em> (\'and I myself will establish my covenant with you\'). The divine-initiative language (<em>ani</em>, I myself) makes the restoration entirely unilateral. The knowledge formula — <em>veyada\'at ki-ani YHWH</em> — places the recognition of YHWH as the goal of the entire process from the foundling rescue to the everlasting covenant.</p>',
    "63": '<p><strong>Silence before YHWH\'s forgiveness</strong>: The final verse of the chapter describes Jerusalem\'s response to the forgiveness: <em>lema\'an tizkerevat uvoshti</em> (\'so that you remember and be ashamed\'). The forgiveness itself produces shame — not the shame of punishment but the shame of grace received by one who does not deserve it. <em>Ufatachti lach peh bemaayen kol-kapparat</em> (\'and you will not open your mouth anymore because of your shame when I have made atonement for you\'): the silencing that comes from undeserved forgiveness. The receipt of grace is the most powerful agent of genuine repentance in Ezekiel\'s theology.</p>'
},
"17": {
    "1": '<p>New oracle. Chapter 17 presents an allegory (<em>chiddah umeshal</em> — riddle and parable) that is rare in Ezekiel in that the text itself provides the interpretation (vv. 11-21). This self-interpreting allegory is a deliberate pedagogical tool: Ezekiel first presents the enigmatic parable, then explains it to prevent misreading.</p>',
    "2": '<p><strong>Chiddah and meshal</strong>: <em>Chiddah</em> is \'riddle/enigma\' — a speech requiring interpretation (cf. Samson\'s riddle in Judg 14:14-18; the Queen of Sheba\'s riddles to Solomon in 1 Kgs 10:1). <em>Meshal</em> is \'proverb/parable/allegory\' — a comparison-speech. The combination signals high literary sophistication: this oracle is not a straightforward pronouncement but a literary puzzle requiring interpretive engagement from the audience. The riddling quality slows the audience toward careful attention.</p>',
    "3": '<p><strong>The great eagle with great wings</strong>: The first eagle (<em>nesher gadol gedol-kanafayim</em>) is immediately identified in v.12 as the king of Babylon (Nebuchadnezzar). The eagle metaphor for imperial power was widespread in ancient Near Eastern iconography: Assyrian royal stelae featured eagle imagery; the Babylonian standard bore a spread eagle; Neo-Babylonian cylinder seals use the eagle as a symbol of divine and royal power. The eagle\'s multicolored plumage and full feathers evoke the military splendor of Babylon at its height.</p>',
    "4": '<p><strong>The top of the cedar cropped and brought to a city of merchants</strong>: The cedar of Lebanon represents the Davidic dynasty (cf. Ps 92:12; Jer 22:23). The "top" (<em>tzameret</em>) = Jehoiachin, who was taken to Babylon in 597 BCE (2 Kgs 24:15). The "city of merchants" (<em>ir koferim</em>) = Babylon, which was the commercial center of the ancient Near East. Babylon took Jehoiachin, the Davidic crown prince, as a political hostage — the standard Mesopotamian practice of keeping vassal royal family members to ensure compliance.</p>',
    "5": '<p><strong>A seed of the land planted in fertile soil</strong>: After cropping the cedar-top (Jehoiachin), Babylon took a seed from the land (<em>mizera ha\'aretz laqach</em>) and planted it by abundant waters — this is Zedekiah, placed as a vassal king by Nebuchadnezzar (2 Kgs 24:17). The "fertile soil" with "abundant waters" describes Zedekiah\'s installed position: a vassal king with resources sufficient for stability under Babylonian suzerainty. The vine-planting metaphor sets up a contrast with the cedar — Zedekiah is not the royal cedar but a planted vine.</p>',
    "6": '<p><strong>The vine grew low and spreading</strong>: The vine\'s low growth (<em>geshafel shefal qomat</em>) and turning toward Babylon (<em>aleyha lifnu lifsanav</em>) describes Zedekiah\'s appropriate vassal posture — growing under Babylonian patronage, branches turned toward the suzerain. The vine was fruitful and produced branches and boughs — Zedekiah\'s reign had stability under Babylonian oversight. The political allegory is straightforwardly positive in this phase: vassal submission, properly maintained, would have preserved Judah.</p>',
    "7": '<p><strong>The second great eagle (Egypt)</strong>: The second eagle (<em>nesher gadol gadol-kanafayim verav-nossot</em>) appears and the vine begins turning its roots and shoots toward it. The second eagle is identified in v.15 as Egypt. Zedekiah\'s appeal to Egypt (2 Kgs 24:20; Jer 37:5-8; 37:11) in violation of his vassal oath to Babylon is the historical referent. Egypt\'s military intervention in 588 BCE briefly disrupted the Babylonian siege of Jerusalem, giving Zedekiah momentary hope before Babylon resumed and completed the conquest.</p>',
    "8": '<p>The vine was well-planted by good water — it had everything it needed to thrive under Babylonian patronage. The shift of allegiance toward Egypt is therefore not driven by necessity but by choice — a choice to seek additional security beyond what the established covenant arrangement provided. The allegory makes clear that the Egyptian alliance was not forced on Zedekiah by inadequate Babylonian provision but was an active rejection of his established relationship.</p>',
    "9": '<p><strong>The divine question: "Will it prosper?"</strong>: <em>Hayitzlach</em> (\'will it succeed?\'): the rhetorical question that already knows the answer — no. The vine\'s roots and branches will be torn off (<em>etkoshen peruteha yibash</em>). The political allegory becomes explicitly predictive: Babylon will return and destroy the vine that turned toward Egypt. <em>Uvelo zeroa gadol uva\'am rav linsoah otah mishorsheha</em> (\'without a great arm or great army to pull it up by its roots\'): the Babylonian reconquest will be effortless — no great military effort needed to destroy the traitorous vassal vine.</p>',
    "10": '<p>The east wind (<em>ruach qadim</em>) — the dry, scorching wind from the desert, standard metaphor for Babylon as the power from the east. The transplanted vine wilted by the east wind anticipates Nebuchadnezzar\'s return after Egypt\'s intervention failed. Historically, Pharaoh Apries\' army (Jer 37:5) briefly interrupted the siege but then withdrew, leaving Jerusalem to its fate. The east wind image was familiar to any Near Eastern audience — the sirocco/khamsin that withers vegetation was as much a part of Levantine experience as it is today.</p>',
    "11": '<p>The transition to the interpretation: <em>Vayehi devar-YHWH elai lemor</em>. The formulaic oracle-reception marks a break between the parable and its explanation. This self-interpreted parable structure is similar to the NT parable interpretations (Mark 4:13-20) — the prophet/teacher provides the key to the allegory rather than leaving it for audience speculation.</p>',
    "12": '<p><strong>The explicit identification of the first eagle</strong>: The "rebellious house" must hear: the great eagle = Babylon; the cedar top = the king of Judah (Jehoiachin); the princes = the Jerusalem leaders taken to Babylon in 597 BCE. The historical specificity of the interpretation anchors the allegory: this is not a generic story about empires but a specific account of the 597 BCE deportation and its political aftermath.</p>',
    "13": '<p><strong>The vassal covenant</strong>: Babylon "took from the royal seed and made a covenant with him" (<em>vayyiqach mizera hammluchah vayyikrot ito brit</em>) — the formal vassal installation of Zedekiah. The oath (<em>alah</em>) imposed on Zedekiah was a suzerain-vassal treaty of the type well attested in Mesopotamian diplomatic practice (Neo-Assyrian vassal treaties [SAA II]; Neo-Babylonian practice). The "mighty of the land" taken away ensure compliance — hostage diplomacy, standard ANE practice.</p>',
    "14": '<p><strong>The purpose of the vassal arrangement</strong>: <em>Lihyot mamlachah shefalah lelo hitNasse\' lishmor et-briti</em> (\'to be a humble/low kingdom, not lifting itself up, to keep his covenant\'). The vassal arrangement\'s explicit purpose — humble submission and covenant fidelity — was entirely achievable. Babylon was not demanding the impossible; a stable vassal relationship was mutually beneficial. The failure was entirely Zedekiah\'s choice to break what could have been maintained.</p>',
    "15": '<p><strong>The rebellion</strong>: <em>Vayyimrod vo lishlach malakhav Mitzraymah</em> (\'but he rebelled by sending messengers to Egypt\'). The political act of appealing to Egypt was ipso facto a breach of the vassal covenant with Babylon. In ANE suzerain-vassal treaty law, seeking alternative alliances without the suzerain\'s permission was a capital political crime. Jer 37:5-8 describes the specific appeal to Pharaoh Apries. The rhetorical question — <em>hayitzlach hammalat yimalet</em> (\'can he who has done this succeed? Can one escape?\'): the expected answer is no.</p>',
    "16": '<p><strong>Death in Babylon</strong>: Zedekiah will die in Babylon (<em>betoch Bavel yamut</em>). 2 Kings 25:6-7 fulfills this: Zedekiah was captured, his sons killed before his eyes, his eyes put out, and he was taken to Babylon where he died in prison (Jer 52:11). The historical details of Zedekiah\'s capture and death are predicted here with specific accuracy that post-event audiences would have recognized. <em>Asher-avazeh elah vasher hafar brit</em>: the broken covenant oath is the theological basis for the judgment.</p>',
    "17": '<p><strong>Egypt\'s failure to help</strong>: <em>Velo bevechayil gadol uvaqahal rav ya\'aseh oto phar\'oh bamil chama</em> (\'and Pharaoh with his great army and many troops will not help him in the war\'): the prediction that Egypt\'s military intervention would be ineffective. Historically accurate — Apries\' army temporarily disrupted the siege but then withdrew (Jer 37:11), leaving Jerusalem to fall. Egypt was the unreliable ally that Isaiah had long warned against (Isa 30:1-5; 31:1-3): \'Egypt is a staff made of reed; it will splinter and pierce the hand of anyone who leans on it\' (Isa 36:6).</p>',
    "18": '<p><strong>The broken oath as the capital crime</strong>: <em>Vavaz alah lehafar brit vehinneh natan yado</em> (\'despising the oath by breaking the covenant — but he gave his hand\'). \'Giving the hand\' is an oath gesture of submission and allegiance (cf. Ezra 10:19; 1 Chr 29:24; 2 Chr 30:8). Zedekiah had given his hand to Babylon in the vassal installation; now he breaks that sworn oath. YHWH\'s indictment: <em>kol-eleh asah lo yimalet</em> (\'after all these things he will not escape\'). The certainty of judgment is grounded in the moral weight of covenant-breaking.</p>',
    "19": '<p><strong>The divine oath</strong>: <em>Lachen koh amar Adonai YHWH chai-ani im-lo alati asher bazah vebrit asher hefar venatati verosho</em> (\'therefore thus says the Lord YHWH: as I live, my oath that he despised and my covenant that he broke I will return on his head\'). The remarkable theological claim: Zedekiah\'s violation of the Babylonian vassal oath is simultaneously a violation of YHWH\'s oath, because YHWH himself is the guarantor of covenants. This principle — that international covenants have divine sanction — underlies the prophetic tradition of judgment on covenant-breaking from Numbers 30:2 through Amos 1-2.</p>',
    "20": '<p><strong>Divine capture and judgment</strong>: <em>Ufraisti alav reshti venikpad birmachti</em> (\'I will spread my net over him and he will be caught in my snare\'): YHWH directly takes responsibility for the capture of Zedekiah. 2 Kings 25:4-7 describes the capture: Zedekiah fled the city and was caught in the plains of Jericho. The divine net-trapping of a fleeing person is a standard ancient Near Eastern royal punishment metaphor — Assyrian inscriptions describe enemies caught in nets like birds.</p>',
    "21": '<p><strong>The fugitives scattered</strong>: All the military forces (<em>mivchar miflotehu</em>) will fall by the sword; survivors will be scattered to every wind. 2 Kings 25:4-7 and Jeremiah 52:7-11 describe the dispersal of the Judean army. The <em>yeda\'tem ki-ani YHWH dibarti</em> formula: even the military catastrophe of the 586 BCE conquest is the enactment of YHWH\'s spoken word — the siege and fall of Jerusalem is a prophetic fulfillment, not merely a military event.</p>',
    "22": '<p><strong>The divine cedar-cutting</strong>: The allegory reverses with YHWH himself taking a cutting. <em>Ve\'anochi iqach min-tzameret ha\'erez haramah</em> (\'and I myself will take from the top of the high cedar\'): YHWH does what Babylon did — takes the cedar top — but for restoration rather than deportation. The Davidic restoration is structurally parallel to the Davidic deportation: the same cedar, the same cropping, but now by divine hand for planting rather than by imperial hand for removal.</p>',
    "23": '<p><strong>The high mountain of Israel</strong>: <em>Behar marom Yisrael</em> — the eschatological Zion, the high mountain of 40:2; Isaiah 2:2-4 (\'the mountain of the Lord\'s temple will be established as the highest of the mountains\'). The planted cedar-twig will grow into a magnificent tree: <em>vehinsa gaz vehaya le\'erez addir</em> (\'and it shall become a stately cedar\'). The birds of every kind will nest under it (<em>tachteha yishchevu kol-tzipor kol-kanaf</em>) — the universal restoration: all nations finding shelter under the Davidic-Messianic tree. The image anticipates the mustard seed parable of Matthew 13:31-32.</p>',
    "24": '<p><strong>All the trees of the field will know</strong>: <em>Veyad\'u kol-atzei hassadeh ki ani YHWH</em> (\'and all the trees of the field will know that I, YHWH\'). The trees — all political powers and kingdoms — will recognize through this reversal that YHWH controls the rise and fall of nations. <em>Ani YHWH shafalt etz gavoa hashpilatiy ve\'et-etz shafel higbahti</em> (\'I, YHWH, bring down the high tree and make the low tree grow\'): the sovereign reversal formula — the principle behind the Magnificat (Luke 1:52) and the entire prophetic tradition of YHWH\'s preferential reversal of human power structures.</p>'
}
}

